item.title: How do i fix this?
item.dc:creator: @the_soul The Soul
item.description:
@the_soul wrote:

ollie123:

Yeah…you can’t call an integer.

Oh really?

public int i; public void callAnInteger() { i = 1; switch(i) { case 1: System.out.println("I called an integer of the value "+i); i = 2; break; case 2: System.out.println("I called an integer of the value "+i); break; } }

It’s not exactly calling an integer, however, it’s still being used elsewhere.

And Oh-Noes: if you’re invoking a method, creating integers won’t solve the problem.

Read full topic

item.title: How do i fix this?
item.dc:creator: @Oh-Noes Oh-Noes
item.description:
@Oh-Noes wrote:

[quote=“ollie123, post:4, topic:318243”][quote author=iKapa link=topic=414735.msg3052792#msg3052792 date=1260214709]
Erm not too good at Java but try going into class client and changing q12help() into q12help();

and same for q13. If that doesn’t work try adding c. to the start.
[/quote][quote author=Oh-Noes link=topic=414735.msg3052797#msg3052797 date=1260214952]
You haven’t declared q12 & q13 as integers in your client class.
Just add:

public int q12; public int q13;
Under:

public class client extends Player implements Runnable {

In your client.java.
[/quote]

Your’e both wrong. This means that the methods names q12help and q13help do not exist in the client class.[/quote]
And how do you fix something that isn’t there… you DECLARE it. Guessing by the name of the integers, I’d say he’s using DeltaScape (or something derived from it) which has integers q1-11 already in the client class.
